A sign of going viral in the digital age is when a meme becomes so popular as to have its origins obscured. Just as the lyrics â€œApna Time Ayegaâ€ (Our Time Will Come) from the 2019 film Gully Boy, â€œHum Kagaz Nahi Dikhayengeâ€, is an exercise in futurity, a promissory gesture of resistance in the face of autocratic power.

This spirit of resistance can be found in another one of my favorite poems from recent weeks, â€œTum Kaun Ho Be?â€, a title while in itself not profane, is probably best translated in tonality to â€œWho the hell are you?â€ Poet Puneet Sharma first released a version of this on YouTube in April 2019. But the poem surged in popularity following a performance of it in Azad Maidan this January, captured on video. A quietly defiant poem, it casts love for oneâ€™s country as private, not demonstrative: â€œLook! I would tell you, but the land herself is restless/ What is between her and me, is somewhat personalâ€. It also casts the patriotism that is the order of the day â€” the kind that requires you to show papers and sing national anthems in movie theatres by mandate, as sasta nasha (cheap high).

